  "prompt": "Is every fossil a missing link?",
  "response": "No, not every fossil is considered a \"missing link.\" The term \"missing link\" is often used to describe a fossil that represents a transitional form between different species or groups, illustrating an evolutionary step. While many fossils provide important information about the evolutionary history of life on Earth, not all of them are transitional forms. Some fossils are of species that might not show significant evolutionary changes or connections between major groups. Therefore, while all fossils contribute to our understanding of the past, only certain fossils are identified as missing links due to their specific position in the evolutionary lineage.",
